#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:1
msgid ""
"Say we have four people and we need to form two teams of two people each."
" We have some information about how well each pair of people work "
"together, and we want to form the teams such that the total "
"\"compatibility\" of the teams is maximized. The information about who "
"likes who is as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:7 ../../shared/team_building.rst:9
msgid "Alice"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:7 ../../shared/team_building.rst:11
msgid "Bob"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:7 ../../shared/team_building.rst:13
msgid "Carol"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:7 ../../shared/team_building.rst:15
msgid "Dave"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:9 ../../shared/team_building.rst:11
#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:13 ../../shared/team_building.rst:15
msgid "N/A"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:9 ../../shared/team_building.rst:11
msgid "1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:9 ../../shared/team_building.rst:13
msgid "3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:9 ../../shared/team_building.rst:15
msgid "4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:11 ../../shared/team_building.rst:13
msgid "5"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:11 ../../shared/team_building.rst:15
msgid "2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:13 ../../shared/team_building.rst:15
msgid "6"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:18
msgid ""
"So this means that Alice would prefer to work with Dave, while Bob would "
"prefer to work with Carol, and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:20
msgid ""
"Mathematically, we can represent our two teams as binary variables, where"
" :math:`x_i` is 0 if person :math:`i` is in team 0, and 1 if they are in "
"team 1. The compatibility of team 0 can then be expressed as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:23
#, python-brace-format
msgid "C_0 = \\sum_{i=0,j=0}^3 p_{ij} (1 - x_i) (1 - x_j)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:27
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Where :math:`p_{ij}` is the compatibility score between person :math:`i` "
"and person :math:`j`. Note that here each term is only non-zero if both "
":math:`x_i` and :math:`x_j` are 0, which means that both people are in "
"team 0. Meanwhile the compatibility of team 1 can be expressed as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:31
#, python-brace-format
msgid "C_1 = \\sum_{i=0,j=0}^3 p_{ij} x_i x_j"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:35
msgid ""
"Thus we want to maximize the total compatibility :math:`C = C_0 + C_1`, "
"subject to the constraint that team 1 (and thus team 0) has exactly two "
"people:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:38
msgid "\\max_{x_i \\in \\{0, 1\\}} C"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:42
#, python-brace-format
msgid "\\text{subject to} \\quad x_{Alice} + x_{Bob} + x_{Carol} + x_{Dave} = 2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:46
msgid ""
"One issue with this formulation is that it has a constraint, which makes "
"it more difficult to solve using quantum optimization algorithms. To fix "
"this, we can use some techniques to turn this into a QUBO (Quadratic "
"Unconstrained Binary Optimization) problem. In this case, since we just "
"have a single equality constraint, we can add a squared version of it to "
"the objective function as a penalty term, such that the penalty term is "
"zero when the constraint is satisfied, and positive otherwise. For more "
"details on this process, check out the :doc:`QUBO reference "
"</modules/core/core_qubo>`. Now we can assume that the problem has been "
"reformulated into the following unconstrained optimization problem:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:53
msgid "\\min_{x_i \\in \\{0, 1\\}} \\sum_{i=0,j=0}^4 c_{ij} x_i x_j"
msgstr ""

#: ../../shared/team_building.rst:57
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Where :math:`c_{ij}` are coefficients that encode the objective function "
"as well as the constraint."
msgstr ""

